{{Use Indian English|date=July 2013}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}
The '''jeep scandal''' in 1948 was first major corruption case in independent India.<ref>{{cite news|title=On Your Marks|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?263904|accessdate=|newspaper=Outlook|date=1 February 2010|location=India}}</ref> [[V.K. Krishna Menon]], the then Indian high commissioner to [[United Kingdom|Britain]], ignored protocols and signed a Rs 80 lakh contract for the purchase of army jeeps with a foreign firm.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Republic of Scams: Jeep purchase (1948)|url=http://news.in.msn.com/gallery.aspx?cp-documentid=5140159&page=1|work=MSN|accessdate=20 December 2011|author=Dipankar Paul|date=30 April 2011}}</ref>

==Corruption allegations==
[[V. K. Krishna Menon]], then the Indian high commissioner to Britain, bypassed protocol to sign a deal worth Rs 80 lakh with a foreign firm for the purchase of 200 army jeeps.<ref>{{cite news|title=Media support crusade against corruption|url=http://www.hindu.com/2011/04/18/stories/2011041851921100.htm|accessdate=|newspaper=The Hindu|date=18 April 2011|location=India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Scamstory|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?204016|accessdate=|magazine=Outlook|date=13 August 1997|location=India}}</ref> While most of the money was paid upfront, just 155 jeeps landed,the then Prime Minister Nehru forced the government to accept them.<ref>{{cite news|title=India bruised and shrunk|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/opinion/tarun-vijay/the-right-view/India-bruised-and-shrunk/articleshow/2761153.cms|accessdate=|newspaper=Times of India|date=6 February 2008|location=India}}</ref> [[Govind Ballabh Pant]] the then [[Minister for Home Affairs (India)|Home Minister]] and the then Government of Indian National Congress announced on 30 September 1955 that the Jeep scandal case was closed for judicial inquiry ignoring suggestion by the Inquiry Committee led by Ananthsayanam Ayyangar.<ref name="Noorani1970">{{cite book | author=Abdul Gafoor Abdul Majeed Noorani | title=India's Constitution and politics |year=1970 | publisher=Jaico | page = 174}}</ref> He declared that "as far as Government was concerned it has made up its mind to close the matter. If the opposition was not satisfied they can make it an election issue". Soon after on 3 February 1956 Krishna Menon was inducted into the Nehru cabinet as minister without portfolio.<ref>http://www.southasiaanalysis.org/%5Cpapers3%5Cpaper219.htm</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatvnews.com/politics/national/worst-political-scandals-of-independent-india-7515.html?page=2|title= Worst political scandals of independent India|publisher=India TV News|accessdate=15 January 2013}}</ref> Later Krishna Menon became Prime Minister Jawaharlal Nehru's trusted ally and the defence minister.

Mahatma Gandhi's Personal Secretary Mr. U V Kalyanam, in a newspaper interview <ref name=NehruManmohanGraft>{{cite news|last1=Rao|first1=G.V.R Subba|title=Nehru, Manmohan to blame for graft|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Vijayawada/nehru-manmohan-to-blame-for-graft/article5897636.ece|accessdate=19 November 2015|issue=April 11, 2014|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref> said, "It is pertinent to mention here that Nehru made corrupt colleagues like Krishna Menon, who was involved in the infamous ‘jeep scam’ while he was the Defence Minister."

